Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Why stabilizers: the exponential wall", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"c4cac16d-4936-4d82-a6c1-8597119acf9a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A pure state of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["n", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "555a7efa-765a-4da4-8e0c-79abf8dc44ba"],
 " qubits is a unit vector in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\:2102", 
   SuperscriptBox["2", 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"]]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "44c6ba82-2d99-4b0f-a967-4f12a32eb09e"],
 ", so writing it down means storing ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["2", 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "93f5e603-0015-45bd-9932-5aab48bd1d54"],
 " complex amplitudes. At ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "=", "20"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8aa2d72a-4daf-450b-9ef7-eb45daad232c"],
 " that is already a million numbers, at ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "=", "50"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6436fb63-39c5-4fa9-b47d-562520b85620"],
 " it exceeds the number of atoms in a building. Yet many of the states we \
care most about, including every state any error-correcting code protects, \
are not generic: they sit at the fixed points of a large group of Pauli \
operators, and that structure can be stored in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["O", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], "2"], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a8e3abf8-a95d-44ed-9016-54c60b63f4f9"],
 " bits."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b917ecc4-f069-4a4b-af0f-cd3bb1363374"],

Cell["\<\
To feel the wall, ask for the dense state vector of a 20-qubit GHZ state and \
look only at its length:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f3dfa01d-6899-4e40-b7b5-632061191c42"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Length", " ", "@", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"QuantumState", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<GHZ\>\"", "[", "20", "]"}], "]"}], "[", "\"\<StateVector\>\"",
    "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[2]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"c8bca4a4-8db8-4774-a0e6-3a50d827e3f7"],

Cell[BoxData["1048576"], "Output",
 CellLabel->"Out[2]= ",ExpressionUUID->"de7af085-661f-4e98-a111-64cf50777edc"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "That is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["2", "20"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ff95662c-1eca-40ce-be0f-39b0c7011068"],
 " amplitudes for a state that, as we will see, is pinned down completely by \
20 short Pauli strings. The stabilizer formalism is the bookkeeping that \
exploits exactly this gap."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2a91ccdd-e88e-40d3-9a5d-852da184ff69"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A state is what fixes it: the single qubit", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"39565408-1726-4217-952c-5954cbadbd2c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The central move is to stop describing a state by its amplitudes and start \
describing it by the operators that leave it invariant. The state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8295931e-faf1-4389-a1fc-e909254aee82"],
 " is the unique ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"+", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8c42b81c-6d39-4d57-8a16-2dd7092de22e"],
 " eigenvector of the Pauli operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["Z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "08027a53-6635-46ce-b468-b78b6d3538e5"],
 ". We say ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["Z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9fb2f648-96ee-4458-9775-45083d2c96fe"],
 " ",
 StyleBox["stabilizes", "TI"],
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "efc4e194-7f80-488f-8234-cab75f1b8a80"],
 ", and since one operator already determines a one-qubit state up to \
normalization, that single fact ",
 StyleBox["is", "TI"],
 " the state."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3588593c-a8f9-48c5-88ec-9f5bb9a20726"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["Z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "137e4472-36b7-4ce4-84e5-622df9930683"],
 " fixes ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "01589a1e-8850-4a55-97f8-512691a30073"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"129f005b-82b4-4a8a-8691-5a35a7398a53"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[3]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"0e22cf03-f844-4d8a-a057-6343e89617c1"],

Cell[BoxData["True"], "Output",
 CellLabel->"Out[3]= ",ExpressionUUID->"ee4538d0-40e4-49f2-9460-bd47c69517ac"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the framework, the one-qubit register ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{"0"},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6fb5e6b9-46ed-472a-bb7a-3279e419895c"],
 " is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"PauliStabilizer", "[", "1", "]"}]], "InlineFormula",ExpressionUUID->
  "83120172-549e-496f-85d7-5ff43833d8ae"],
 ". The object prints as a summary box that shows its generators and, for \
small systems, its tableau, so the cheap representation is the thing you \
see:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"797c5501-ceac-4827-835d-8d90aef2a0de"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

